05209nam a22008055i 9780231548939DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018026113  a97802315489397 a10.7312/scot190462doi  a(DE-B1597)517727  a(OCoLC)1080078536  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aLC72.2b.S38 2019 4aLC72.2b.S38 2019 7aEDU0160002bisacsh04a378.1/2132231 aScott, Joan Wallach, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aKnowledge, Power, and Academic Freedom /cJoan Wallach Scott. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Wellek Library Lectures00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction: On the Future of Academic Freedom -- t1. Academic Freedom as an Ethical Practice -- t2. Knowledge, Power, and Academic Freedom -- t3. Civility, Affect, and Academic Freedom -- t4. Academic Freedom and the State -- t5. On Free Speech and Academic Freedom -- tEpilogue: In the Age of Trump, a Chilling Atmosphere - An Interview with Joan Wallach Scott -- tNOTES -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAcademic freedom rests on a shared belief that the production of knowledge advances the common good. In an era of education budget cuts, wealthy donors intervening in university decisions, and right-wing groups threatening dissenters, scholars cannot expect that those in power will value their work. Can academic freedom survive in this environment—and must we rearticulate what academic freedom is in order to defend it?This book presents a series of essays by the renowned historian Joan Wallach Scott that explore the history and theory of free inquiry and its value today. Scott considers the contradictions in the concept of academic freedom. She examines the relationship between state power and higher education; the differences between the First Amendment right of free speech and the guarantee of academic freedom; and, in response to recent campus controversies, the politics of civility. The book concludes with an interview conducted by Bill Moyers in which Scott discusses the personal experiences that have informed her views. Academic freedom is an aspiration, Scott holds: its implementation always falls short of its promise, but it is essential as an ideal of ethical practice. Knowledge, Power, and Academic Freedom is both a nuanced reflection on the tensions within a cherished concept and a strong defense of the importance of critical scholarship to safeguard democracy against the anti-intellectualism of figures from Joseph McCarthy to Donald Trump.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aAcademic freedomzUnited States. 0aEducation, HigherxAims and objectiveszUnited States. 0aHigher education and statezUnited States. 0aLearning and scholarshipzUnited States. 7aEDUCATION / History.2bisacsh1 aMoyers, Bill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065195908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics, Law & Social Sciences 2019 ENGz978311061013008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2019z9783110606485oZDB-23-DSW40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/scot1904640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231548939423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231548939.jpg  a978-3-11-061013-0  EBOOK PACKAGE E